shire): variant of   Wetherington  ."]},{"name":"Witherington","meanings":["English: either a variant of   Wetherington  , or perhaps a habitational name from Witherenden in Ticehurst (Sussex), Witherden Farm in Headcorn (Kent), or a lost place called <i>Witherington</i> or similar. The Sussex and Kent placenames probably derive from an Old English personal name <i>Wither</i> + Old English connective <i>-ing-</i> + <i>denn</i> ‘woodland pasture’."]}]},{"name":"Gerard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. It is derived from <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’ + <i>hard</i> ‘brave, hardy, strong’. In the later Middle Ages this was a more common name than   Gerald  , with which it was sometimes confused. Nowadays it is less common, surviving mainly among Roman Catholics, in honour of the many saints of this name."],"variants":[{"name":"Gerrard","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Gerard  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"Jerrard","meanings":["Rare variant spelling of   Gerard  , probably influenced by the form of the modern surname, if not a transferred use."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":10,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":35,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Gerard de Widdrington was born in 1280, in Widdrington, Nort